Han Hao Poster WPA 2019

Header row

The Impact of Auditory Distraction on Reading Comprehension
An Individual Differences Investigation

Han Hao & Andrew R. A. Conway Claremont Graduate University
Han Hao han.hao@cgu.edu osf.io/3ug4k github.com/hansingle

Body row

Introduction

Research Question

Does auditory distraction impair reading comprehension performances across different settings?

Motivation

The Disfluency Effect: Perceptually Difficult task may improve performance (e.g.hard-to-read font)
The Shield Effect: disfluency manipulation can shield attention from being imparied by distractions
Individual Differences: Working Memory Capacity, attention, and reading comprehension

The Present Study

A replication and extension of Halin et al.(2014) on the shield effect in an applied setting of reading comprehension
Investigating the effect of auditory distraction, perceptual difficulty, and working memory capacity on reading task performance

Halin et al.(2014) The Present study

Method

Design & Participants

2 by 3 Mixed Factorial, N = 33 + 40
Font: Easy-to-read vs.Hard-to-read
Distraction: Speech / Meaningless / No noise

Procedure & Materials

WMC Tasks: Rspan & Rotspan
Reading Tests: 3 Reading tests under 3 levels of distractions
Manipulation Checks: Reading speed and subjective perception of difficulty

Results

No difference in reading speed between two fonts
Reading with no distraction was preceived to be easier
Group Level: Main effect of distraction, no main effect of font or interaction
Individual Level: No individual difference across or within subjects

Footer row

Conclusion

Halin et al.(2014) not replicated: Perceptual difficulty did not shield task performances from being impaired by auditory distraction.
Overall, task performance is impaired when a background noise exists.
The sheild effect of disfluency on reading tasks is not of enough reliability.

Future Research

More trials and larger sample size
Complex cognitive tasking vs.perception level processing
Testing on the memory or perception of Distraction
